<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / French Elections: Le Pen lashes out at 'unjust' system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT ONLY needed his extreme National Front to gain around 12 per cent in
yesterday's first round vote - a couple of points higher than the extreme
right-wing movement was scoring in the campaign opinion polls - to relaunch
its leader, Mr Jean-Marie Le Pen, into rhetorical orbit.
'It was scandalous', said Mr Le Pen, that the Communists with a lower vote
of 8-9 per cent could get two dozen seats, while the National Front would at
best get only two seats.
The reason, of course, is that the Communist vote benefits from the majority
voting system by being geographically concentrated, while the support of the
National Front, like that of the Greens, is spread thinly.
This 'unjust and anti-democratic system' must be changed, insisted Mr Le
Pen.
The National Front's one incumbent deputy, Ms Marie-France Stirbois, said
yesterday she thought her party's score was excellent, particularly in view
of the fact that the National Front started the race for the parliamentary
seats with 'shoes of lead' because all the media publicity was focused on
the ecologists, rather than the extreme right.
There was no early result from the Nice seat for which Mr Le Pen is running.
He himself said his party's support was 30-40 per cent up on its score in
the 1986 and 1988 National Assembly elections, conveniently ignoring the
fact that it also constituted a decline from the 13.9 per cent which it
gained more recently in last year's regional elections.
The National Front yesterday did well enough for up to 90 of its candidates
to go on to the second ballot on March 28, the leader claimed. Generally,
these candidates would not stand down in favour of other parties'
candidates, though Mr Le Pen hinted that there might be some switching of
support to mainstream Gaullist/centre-right candidates whom the Front
regarded as 'good'.
</TEXT>
