<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / French Elections: Rocard's career in the balance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michel Rocard, the Socialists' expected standard-bearer in the 1995
presidential elections, was last night fighting to keep his political career
alive.
The ex-prime minister, who headed the Socialist government in 1988-91, was
predicted by the opinion polls to have gained only 28.2 per cent support in
his suburban Paris constituency, easily outdistanced by his Gaullist RPR
challenger, Mr Pierre Cardo, who received 38.8 per cent.
Hoping to turn this around in next Sunday's second ballot by gaining the
left-wing support outside the Socialist party, Mr Rocard said that the
Socialists' generally disastrous performance underlined 'the degree to which
we (the Socialists) need to transform our party, to rally other elements' of
the left. Mr Rocard was referring to his recent call for 'a big bang'
recomposition of the French left.
To mark a certain distance from President Francois Mitterrand and the
current Socialist government of which he is not a member, Mr Rocard
described the defeat as only 'partially unmerited'.
As recently as last Wednesday, Mr Rocard repeated open criticism of Mr
Mitterrand, saying that the president had failed following his 1988
presidential victory to reach out properly to parties to the left and centre
of the Socialists. The president, said Mr Rocard, had chosen to deal 'with
individuals and not with political forces'.
Last night Mr Rocard urged Socialists to join other sympathetic political
forces, particularly the badly battered Greens, to limit the right's further
gains in next weekend's second ballot.
</TEXT>
