<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / Italian probe claims scalp of fourth minister
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Gianni Fontana, Italy's agriculture minister, last night became the
fourth minister to resign in little more than a month as a result of the
political corruption scandal.
The move is a further serious blow to the fragile eight-month-old government
of Prime Minister Giuliano Amato. Beside the forced departures, he has had
to contend with growing difficulties in passing legislation.
Mr Fontana, a Christian Democrat, stepped down after being told by
magistrates in the northern city of Verona he could face prosecution on
allegations of abusing laws on financing political parties and illegally
receiving funds. Yesterday, magistrates searched Mr Fontana's house in the
city and his holiday home on Lake Garda as part of corruption inquiries in
Verona which have already involved a number of local politicians
Meanwhile, Mr Alfredo Vito, a Christian Democrat MP from Naples advised by
magistrates he could face prosecution in the scandal, has admitted to
collecting billions of lire in bribes for local party leaders. The admission
could give southern magistrates investigating allegations of widespread
political corruption their first breakthrough in one of the electoral
strongholds of Italy's largest political party.
Until now, the investigations, which began in Milan, have barely penetrated
the political fabric of the Mezzogiorno, or southern Italy, where the
Christian Democrats and the Socialists, the two parties most implicated in
the corruption scandal, draw much of their support.
Bribes and kickbacks to politicians 'are present in every corner of
society', said Mr Vito in television interviews at the weekend. 'I was a
part of this system.' Threatening to take the lid off a decade of political
corruption in Naples, Mr Vito has resigned from the party and will step down
as an MP. 'I hope other colleagues under investigation will follow my
example,' he said.
Mr Vito is closely associated with Mr Antonio Gava, a senior Christian
Democrat senator and leader of an important party faction. Naples is also
the power base for two other top Christian Democrats: Mr Vincenzo Scotti,
the former interior minister, and Mr Paolo Cirino Pomicino, the ex-budget
minister.
The allegations against Mr Vito, who received over 100,000 personal
preference votes in last April's general election, involve corruption and
extortion. Last week, a parliamentary committee backed the request by
magistrates, investigating a jobs-for-votes scam, for Mr Vito's immunity to
be waived. On Thursday, he offered to testify voluntarily.
The investigations in Naples, Italy's third biggest city, have focused
partly on alleged kickbacks paid by building contractors for modernising the
football stadium for the 1990 World Cup.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
