<PROFILE>_AN-DCVCFAELFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930320
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 93 / Government faces new row in bid to save pits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S problems over the future of Britain's coal industry
deepened last night as it emerged that a five-month review had failed to
provide a guaranteed future for any of the 31 threatened pits.
The Department of Trade and Industry is preparing to publish a white paper
on coal by April 2 even though its concedes it is not possible to secure
deals by then with generators to take additional coal supplies.
Its decision will increase fears that only a handful of the 31 pits have a
long-term future. It also means that thousands of miners' jobs will remain
under threat for several months longer.
A white paper without guarantees will also lay the government open to
potential further rebellion by dissident Tory MPs.
Labour will charge that the all-party trade and industry select committee
was able to produce a formula for saving at least half the 31 pits by the
end of January.
The white paper will stress limitations on expanding the market for coal but
is unlikely to say how many tonnes extra can be created in the market for
coal, or how many pits can be saved.
The publication date will depend on when, and if, the negotiations for the
base contracts between British Coal and the electricity companies can be
concluded. Officials in the Department of Trade and Industry are expected to
work over the weekend to resolve remaining issues through binding
arbitration.
Although considerable progress was made in negotiations in the last two
days, some regional electricity companies are still saying they do not want
to sign anything before the white paper is published. Mr Michael Heseltine,
trade and industry secretary, has said the contracts must be signed before
the white paper.
A compromise is likely. Even if the problems over base tonnages can be
resolved, talks with the generators for additional contracts are some way
off conclusion. It is these negotiations which will determine how many of
the 31 pits can remain open.
The white paper will stress that the future of mines should be determined by
the market. It is likely to offer the prospect of providing subsidies to
keep open some of the threatened pits but will leave the detail of how many
to negotiations between British Coal and the generators.
This is likely to take several months. Meanwhile, as a prelude to
privatisation of the coal industry, the government will arrange for private
mining companies to lease pits which are not wanted by British Coal. Leasing
talks cannot begin before the white paper is published and are likely to be
lengthy.
The government is likely to signal the first stage in the privatisation of
British Coal in the white paper, but will need to pass legislation before
any pits are sold off. It is thought that the earliest date of publication
for the white paper would be Thursday next week.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Coal Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
