<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 93 / Ministers braced for rebellion on coal industry white paper
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is preparing to risk another political row over the coal
industry by publishing a white paper in the next two weeks before it has won
any guarantees to keep open some of the 31 threatened pits.
Ministers want to lay the white paper before parliament by April 2 even
though they have conceded it will not be possible to conclude negotiations
with generators for coal tonnages additional to those in 'base' contracts
nearing conclusion.
Their decision comes five months after launching a coal review prompted by
the furore over the closure decision. It means that the future of thousands
of threatened miners' jobs will remain uncertain for several months longer.
It will also lay the government open to potential further rebellion by
dissident Tory MPs. Labour will charge that the all-party trade and industry
select committee was able to produce a formula for saving at least half the
31 pits by the end of January.
The date of the white paper will depend on when, and if, the negotiations
for the base contracts between British Coal and the electricity companies
can be concluded. Officials in the Department of Trade and Industry are
expected to work over the weekend to resolve remaining issues through
binding arbitration.
Although considerable progress was made in negotiations in the last two
days, some regional electricity companies are still saying they do not want
to sign anything before the white paper is published. Mr Michael Heseltine,
trade and industry secretary, has said the contracts must be signed before
the white paper.
A compromise is likely. But even if the problems over base tonnages can be
resolved, talks with the generators for additional contracts are some way
off conclusion. It is these negotiations which will determine how many of
the 31 pits can remain open.
The white paper will stress that the future of mines should be determined by
the market. It is likely to offer the prospect of providing subsidies to
keep open some of the threatened pits but will leave the detail of how many
to the outcome of negotiations between British Coal and the generators.
This is likely to take several months. Meanwhile, as a prelude to
privatisation of the coal industry, the government will arrange for private
mining companies to lease pits which are not wanted by British Coal. Leasing
talks cannot begin before the white paper is published.
</TEXT>
<XX>
