<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Gardiner shuffles board for new start
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GARDINER GROUP, the distributor of security and surveillance equipment,
yesterday dismissed its chief executive and announced sweeping board changes
following an investigation into a Pounds 4.8m overstatement in its 1991
accounts.
Mr Yashar Turgut has been replaced as chief executive by Mr Harvey Samson,
group finance director.
Mr Turgut's departure follows a report by accountants Price Waterhouse which
concluded that the company's accounting records had been falsified.
According to Price Waterhouse, there had been a deliberate mis-statement in
the value of the company's stocks, mainly of burglar alarms.
Mr Ian Nellist, group finance director during the period when the
mis-statement took place, 'has so far been unwilling to discuss the matter
with Price Waterhouse or the board', the company told shareholders
yesterday.
Anxious for a new start following the four-month investigation, the company
said Mr Samson would be joined on the board by Mr Richard Clemons as
chairman, replacing Mr Thomas Buffet who resigned last November; Mr Bob
Underhill, a former executive director at Stirling Group, has been named as
finance director.
Announcing a Pounds 2.05m pre-tax profit on turnover of Pounds 73.8m in the
year to October 31 1992, the company claimed it was now ready for expansion
in Britain and continental Europe.
Earnings were 1.34p and a final dividend of 0.19p makes a 0.66p (1.3p)
total.
