<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 93 / Letter: Lesson not learned on stocks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr A C HAKEN.
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your report, 'More heavy job cuts expected soon at Daf' (March 16), of
impending further job losses at Leyland Daf mentions the unacceptably high
stock levels found by the receivers. Sophisticated organisations in both
manufacturing and retailing sectors learned long ago the importance of
obliging their suppliers to make deliveries 'just in time'. That Leyland
Daf's management appears to have failed in this respect is a sad comment on
its competence and justification for complaint by the workforce. It would be
interesting to know what over-stocking arose from the import of components
from the parent company and its overseas subsidiaries.
Anthony Haken,
Bay Cottage,
31 Lower Street,
Horning, Norfolk NR1 8AA
</TEXT>
