<DATE>930320
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 93 / Leading Article: World on the trade brink
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
TRADE FRICTION is increasingly undermining western co-operation. As a
result, short-sighted decisions made by myopic decision-makers could do
untold damage to the hopes of billions of people around the world.
The background is inauspicious. With the collapse of the former Soviet
Union, the strategic glue binding the western economies, has dissolved.
Where once there was a nuclear-armed colossus to fear, there are now beggars
to shrug aside. To its credit, the Clinton administration wants the west to
unite to help rebuild Russia. Unfortunately, squabbles over how to share the
burden now divide the west, whereas the threat once presented by the Soviet
Union united it.
The less than happy state of most major economies makes co-operation still
more difficult. The exception is the US. This week's announcement that US
industrial output was up 0.4 per cent in February and 4.3 per cent over the
past 12 months confirms that Mr Clinton must be the luckiest - and Mr George
Bush the unluckiest - politician on earth.
Others have been less fortunate. The UK economy may now be recovering after
its two and a half years or so in recession, but only after a policy volte
face forced upon a reluctant government by the foreign exchange markets.
In the other major industrial countries, the picture is darker still. The
British Treasury forecasts a fall of  3/4 per cent in the combined gross
domestic product of the three largest continental European economies in
1993, following an increase of just 1 1/4 per cent last year. German GDP may
even fall by 1 1/2 per cent this year, it argues. Yet neither the grim
economic tidings nor the much vaunted 'solidarity pact' have been enough to
transform the Bundesbank's caution. For the rest of Europe, the Bundesbank's
monetary policy feels like the death of a thousand small interest rate cuts.
Further stimulus
Meanwhile, the Japanese government is contemplating a second major fiscal
package, to follow the Y10,700bn (Pounds 62.5bn) emergency increase in
public works spending announced last autumn. Since the British Treasury's
forecast is for a mere 1 per cent increase in Japanese gross national
product between 1992 and 1993, following 1.5 per cent last year, a further
boost would seem inevitable. But the trade surplus, which reached Dollars
10.55bn in February alone, is the most important reason for action, since it
has become an increasingly significant focus of tension, particularly with
the US.
Yet the Japanese trade surplus is as much an excuse for friction as its
cause. Washington is now in the grip of what looks increasingly like a new
policy paradigm, one that is bound to make all its trade relationships more
difficult. Where once US trade policy was aimed at agreements on legal and
administrative processes, it is now aimed more and more at achieving
specific quantitative results. Where once it was multilateral, it is now
increasingly bilateral or unilateral.
Specific commitment
The prime example of the new policy paradigm is the 1986 semiconductor pact,
progress on which is due to be reviewed by US and Japanese trade officials
in Hawaii this weekend. For many Americans this is the example of how trade
should be conducted with Japan. They particularly like the specific
commitment to a 20 per cent foreign share of the Japanese market which they
believe it contained. To this, the Japanese reply that there was no such
commitment. They also assert that no market economy could make such a
commitment. Fortunately, the immediate dispute has been defused by the news
that the Japanese have reached the 'target' they insist is no target at all.
While the US is apparently intent on turning Japan into the 'Japan Inc' that
many Americans complain it already is, it has not ignored its trade
relations with the European Community. Fortunately, the threat of immediate
US sanctions over public procurement has been lifted. But US policy towards
the Uruguay Round of multilateral trade negotiations remains extremely
obscure.
It is an obscurity that some in the EC, particularly the government most
likely to emerge from the coming French elections, may well want to exploit.
That government will, after all, be elected largely because the economy
suffers from rising unemployment and is burdened by short-term real interest
rates at around 8 per cent. Protectionism is almost inevitable. The French
conservative parties are already committed to reviewing the farm reform of
the EC. They are also committed to changing the agreement on farm trade
negotiated with the US last year. Since the US apparently wants precisely
the same thing, further conflict would seem inevitable.
The mistake on all sides of these trade squabbles has been the failure to
recognise that harmonious trade relations have become more central to the
industrial countries not less. It would be a bitter irony if it took the
collapse of Russia's reforming government to restore the co-operation among
the industrial countries that is now so sorely lacking.
</TEXT>
