<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 93 / London road jams 'sickly': Fear of 'maglignant' congestion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR ALASTAIR MORTON, chief executive of Eurotunnel, yesterday warned that if
congestion in and around London was not tackled the rest of Britain would
suffer.
He told a conference of 250 managers in Wakefield, West Yorkshire, that
congestion in London was 'a sickly thrombosis - it's a malignant one, almost
cancerous'.
Speakers at the conference discussed the problems that northern and Scottish
companies have when trying to reach markets in continental Europe.
Lord Healey, the former Labour deputy leader, said northern England and
Scotland had more than 30 per cent of Britain's road freight traffic but
received only 16 per cent of the government's budget for new motorways and
trunk roads.
</TEXT>
