<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 93 / Supreme court judge to quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JUSTICE Byron White yesterday announced his retirement from the Supreme
Court, thus handing President Bill Clinton a first and early opportunity to
begin reshaping the highest court.
Justice White, who is 75, said that after 31 years 'someone else should be
permitted to have a like experience.'
Appointed by President Kennedy in 1962, he is the only nominee of a
Democratic president now sitting on the court.
Not since 1967, when President Johnson elevated the late Justice Thurgood
Marshall, has a vacancy occurred during a Democrat presidency.
At least one other member of the court, Justice Harry Blackmun, has recently
spoken openly about retiring. Though appointed by President Nixon, he has
emerged as one of the most liberal members, whereas Justice White has become
more conservative.
Two names most frequently mentioned as likely Clinton nominations are
governor Mario Cuomo of New York and Mrs Marian Wright Edelman, guiding
light behind the Children's Defence Fund and a close friend of the president
and his wife.
</TEXT>
