<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / International Company News: Costain peace pact with Peabody
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COSTAIN, the UK construction company, yesterday made peace with Peabody
Resources, part of Britain's Hanson conglomerate, and agreed to sell its
Australian coal-mining assets to Peabody for Dollars 200m plus a net asset
adjustment.
The additional asset adjustment is subject to a final audit, but is
estimated to add around Dollars 34m to the purchase price at current
exchange rates. Peabody will also assume around Dollars 65m-worth of
borrowings at the Australian coal operations.
The deal between Costain and Peabody comes at the end of a long and stormy
legal battle in the Missouri courts. The transaction is now expected to be
completed 'shortly' and Peabody and Costain will dismiss their respective
lawsuits against each other. They will also drop claims and counter-claims
for damages and costs.
The lawsuits arose after Costain walked away from its original deal to sell
the Australian coal assets to Peabody for Dollars 200m. Instead, the British
construction group announced that it would sell the business to Altus
Finance for Dollars 245m. Both Altus and Peabody would have assumed ADollars
120m of debt.
Peabody sued, claiming that it had exclusive negotiating rights with Costain
over the assets and, in February, a US judge granted a permanent injunction
preventing Costain from selling the operations to the French buyer. At that
point, Peabody said that it hoped to proceed with the purchase, and talks
with Costain restarted.
