<PROFILE>_AN-DCSB4AGNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930319
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / OFT life insurance proposals: SIB plan dismissed as
anti-competitive
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Office of Fair Trading has produced two reports. The first, under the
Financial Services Act 1986, is a direct reaction to the rules for
investment regulation proposed by SIB and Lautro in July.
The OFT argues that SIB's proposed rules are anti-competitive because they
do not give consumers enough information to make informed choices of brands,
products or sales outlets.
It suggests changes to these proposed rules in four areas:
Disclosure of surrender values in the later years of a policy: under SIB's
rules the surrender values investors would receive if they stopped paying
premiums only need to be shown for the first five years of the policy. The
report finds that surrender values in later years are relevant to a decision
on whether to buy the policy in question, 'or indeed any life product'.
Disclosure of companies' charges in illustrations of future investment
returns: life companies currently publish projections of the likely future
returns on their policies on the basis of an average charge for the
industry. They are not allowed to publish illustrations using their own
charges, even if they are substantially different. The report says these
rules mean that investors will 'make different decisions from those they
would make if they had better information'.
Commission disclosure by independent financial advisers: the report says:
'Without early automatic disclosure of commissions, in actual cash amounts,
an investor will not know the price of advice and cannot compare it with
that for the advice of other IFAs (including those remunerated by fees).'
The commission of agents tied to one company was not within the scope of the
OFT's report, and they would not be obliged to disclose commission. Sir
Bryan Carsberg, OFT director-general, said there were technical difficulties
in forcing disclosure on tied agents but that a method of revealing their
commission 'would be something very much to be welcomed'.
He added that independent advisers operated in two markets - 'the market for
independent financial advice, and the market for selling life insurance'. He
said: 'There has to be a price which is paid for that advice, and as nothing
else is paid, commission must be regarded as that price. The market doesn't
work very well unless people can tell what they are paying.'
Differential pricing among tied outlets: life offices are not allowed under
current SIB rules to offer the same product at different prices through
different tied agents, such as building societies, although the costs
involved for the different agents may vary. According to the OFT this limits
the likelihood that 'the most efficient means of distribution will prevail
and reduce overall costs to investors'.
The OFT is happy with the rules for disclosing an adviser's status (whether
independent or tied) and dis-closure of product details.
In a separate report the OFT sets out a different structure for investor
protection in life insurance sales. Here the OFT calls for transparency of
persistency rates. Companies would have to tell prospective consumers the
percentage of clients who hold their policies to maturity.
Sir Bryan suggested that companies be required to disclose two rates; the
proportion of policyholders remaining after two years and the proportion
which hold policies to maturity. Poor persistency rates are regarded as
evidence that companies sell inappropriate policies to consumers.
The OFT urges that policyholders should receive annual statements similar to
those received by shareholders or unit trust holders. The documents would
give policyholders information about the latest investment returns and say
whether investments were performing better or worse than expected.
Two reports by the director-general of fair trading, published by the Office
of Fair Trading:
The Marketing and Sale of Investment-linked Insurance Products available
from Mr Jayatilleke on 071 269 8794.
Fair Trading and Life Insurance Savings Products available from Mr Arnopp on
071 269 8816.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
What they tell us and what they don't
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Information                              At         SIB        OFT
                                       present    proposal  proposal
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Reduction in yield                       Yes        Yes        Yes
Wealth warnings                          No         Yes        Yes
Adviser's status                         No         Yes        Yes
Five-year surrender values               No         Yes        Yes
Later surrender values                   No         No         Yes
Indenpendent advisers' commission        No         No         Yes
Companies' total charges                 No         No         Yes
Tied agents' commission                  No         No         No
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: FT
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
