<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / World Trade News: Canada takes toughline on Nafta curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEGOTIATIONS on side agreements to the North American Free Trade Agreement
ran into their first obstacle yesterday when Canadian and Mexican chief
negotiators took a tough line against the use of formal trade sanctions to
enforce labour and environmental standards.
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US Trade Representative, has taken on board demands
from prominent US senators and congressmen for agreements 'with teeth', but
he has yet to define how he sees the enforcement taking place.
Yesterday Mr John Weekes, the top Canadian negotiator, said Mr Herminio
Blanco Mendoz and Mr Rufus Yerxa, deputy US Trade Representative had
'exchanged concepts' on the agreements but had reached no firm conclusions .
Negotiators are expected to have little difficulty agreeing to establish
labour and environmental commissions, but trouble is expected in agreeing
their precise powers.
Mr Weekes said he would be consulting with the provinces, the
non-governmental organisations and the business representatives before
determining Canada's final positions.
He also implied that Mexico and Canada had no interest in writing a third
agreement over import surges because that was already embodied in the
completed Nafta text.
Negotiators will meet again on April 11. A deal is expected to take two to
three months, Mr Weekes said. This could get Nafta to the US Congress in
early summer.
</TEXT>
