<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you are more interested in the arts than in American movies, American
comedies, or steam train drama (a repeat of All Creatures Great And Small on
BBC1, and another episode in the new series of Doctor Finlay on ITV) there
is only one programme for you on television tonight: Arena. This, too, has
an American subject: writer Philip Roth, still best known to British readers
for his 1969 novel, Portnoy's Complaint. Previously Roth has tended to stay
off the promotion circuit but now, having written a new book, Operation
Shylock, he is putting himself about like all the others (9.30 BBC1). On
radio, however, there is much wider choice. On Radio 2's Arts Programme
(10.00), Austin Mitchell visits Durham Cathedral which has been declared a
World Heritage Site. Radio 3 offers Strange Meeting in which Russell Davies
considers the achievements of Wilfred Owen who was born 100 years ago and
died at the Sambre Canal in 1918 one week before the armistice (10.45). And
on Radio 4 in Kaleidoscope Roddy Doyle talks about his new book, Paddy
Clarke Ha Ha Ha which draws on his childhood in the 1960s (9.15).
</TEXT>
